The Lost City is a modern caravan label. Its formal name in surviving Measure Script and Salt Ledger inscriptions is Khepra-Lesh, translated as The Court Between Waters and Graves.
Khepra-Lesh was a jurisdictional hinge-city built where oasis water-law administration, pyramid funerary jurisdiction, and eastern desert caravan law all overlapped.
Its founding charter described the city as a balancing court preventing either oasis councils or pyramid priesthoods from monopolizing desert authority.
The city was sustained by a subsidiary branch of the Deepwell Confluence fed by managed draw from the same aquifer network supporting the three oases; water arrived by legal schedule, not geographic inevitability.
Public squares doubled as flow adjudication courts; taxation terms used volumetric units rather than coin; police powers were tied to canal gates and ration tablets.
The Twin-Sovereign period forced Khepra-Lesh to execute both Sand Sovereign and Moon Sovereign law through the same institutions, producing double rulings in which one case was adjudicated under surface law and once under tomb law.
The city fell through a sequence of institutional failures: water schedules collapsed, court authority split between solar docket officers and moon registry keepers, caravan trust eroded, mortuary militias formed, cistern sabotage began.
Great Oasis gave Khepra-Lesh legal prestige, Northern Oasis gave it procedural discipline, Southern Oasis gave it crisis-era function.
Architecture that remains: obelisk gate bearings aligned to caravan vectors, dual-ledger walls recording route distance and legal obligations in the same inscription columns, cistern court architecture placing judges, scribes, and sluice operators in one chamber.
Present factions in the ruins include Dust Charter Scavengers, Cistern Oath Remnants, Meridian Schism Zealots, Tyrant Crypt Adjutants, and Jackal Synod Opportunists.
The Hollow Diadem at the depth of the Tyrant Crypt Ring is the final adjudicator who assumed emergency sovereign powers and fused office, judgment, and burial protocol into one permanent mandate.
The city did not vanish in a sandstorm; it petrified into competing emergency regimes until both ran out of water, personnel, and legitimacy.

